<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-381-174  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 381 174.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  April 23 1990 v7 n16 p9(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Sky accelerator boosts DEC RISC workstations to 80Mflops, 53MVUPs. (Sky Computers introduces SKybolt coprocessor board)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Patch, Kimberly.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Sky Computers Inc announces Skybolt, a new version of itscoprocessor board that incorporates Intel i860 and i960 reducedinstruction set computing (RISC) processors.andP;  Skybolt can boostthe performance of DEC workstations to 83 million floating pointoperations per second, a rating of 53 MicroVAX units of processing(MVUPs.) The application accelerator takes advantage of the160MBps bandwidth between the i860 and memory by using fastmemory.andP;  It is available in static and dynamic RAM configurations.andO;The SRAM version holds up to 8Mbytes of memory, while the DRAMunit can contain up to 16Mbytes of dynamic memory as well as a256Kbyte SRAM cache.andP;  Prices for the Skybolt range from $12,450 to$20,000.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Sky Computers Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Sky Computers Skybolt (Coprocessor) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Performance ImprovementWorkstationsCoprocessorsAccelerator Boards-Cards.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Sky accelerator boosts DEC RISC workstations to 80 Mflops, 53 MVUPsandM;CHELMSFORD, Mass.andP;  -- Sky Computers has announced a co-processor board thatpushes the power of the DECstation 5000 considerably higher than its24.33-MicroVAX II unit of processing (MVUP) rating.andM;Sky officials said a new version of its Skybolt application accelerator,using Intel's i860 and i960 processors, will increase DEC's most powerfulRISC workstations to as much as 53 MVUPs and 80 Mflops.andM;The Skybolt application accelerator for the DECstation 5000 Model 200 usesthe 64-bit i860 for integer, floating-point and graphic computations, whilethe i960 handles I/O functions, system diagnostics and boot functions.andM;&quot;The Intel i860 RISC processor is a very good numerical processor; however,it does have some shortcomings in handling interrupts and other issues,&quot; saidCimarron Boozer, Sky's industry marketing manager.andP;  &quot;We have used it as amachine to do the math and [used the] i960 for I/O, [and therefore we're]getting I/O and math done at the same time,&quot; he said.andM;The board has as much as 16MB of memory that is shared with the mainprocessor, a direct-memory-access engine and a 32-bit, 54MB-per-second linkto the DECstation and other devices.andM;&quot;Between the i860 and memory there is a 160MB-per-second bandwidth.andP;  To takeadvantage of that you must have memory that is fast enough and a system thatcan feed the i860 and keep it busy,&quot; Boozer said.andM;The two memory configurations available on the accelerator board are bothdesigned to do this, according to Boozer.andM;One configuration will use as much as 8MB of static RAM (SRAM) memory; asecond will use a 256KB SRAM cache with as much as 16MB of dynamic RAM(DRAM).andM;Included with the accelerator board are a pair of compilers, assemblylanguage tools and application support libraries.andP;  The Skyvec C and F77compilers are based on Mitaware's High C and Lahey's Fortran f77L software,respectively.andM;Compilers include an embedded vectorizing module that produces vectorizedcode during compilation, a tactic usually taken by supercomputers.andP;  &quot;We'vetaken those compilers and added our own scheduling and vectorizingcapabilities,&quot; he said.andM;&quot;We essentially allowed the front ends of those compilers to generate anintermediate language and we [put] our own optimizations on thoseintermediate languages.andP;  The advantage is when we make improvements [theywill] work with both Fortran and C compilers,&quot; he said.andM;The DECstation 5000-compatible application accelerator will be available inthe third quarter.andP;  Prices range from $12,450 for a version with 500KB ofSRAM to about $20,000 for a version with 16MB of DRAM.andM;Sky is planning a Turbochannel bus-compatible version of the board that willhave as much as 64MB of memory for the first quarter of next year, Boozersaid.andM;Sky Computers Inc. can be contacted at 27 Industrial Ave., Chelmsford, MA01824, (508) 250-1920.andO;</TEXT></DOC>